    'Usually when people do communion (the Lord’s Supper), they either have a wafer, a small square of cracker bread, or people tear off a piece of normal bread. In Jewish culture, they use matzo (or matzah) bread (which is pretty much an over-sized cracker that’s about 4”–6” on either side). They don’t have leaven (yeast), which is symbolic of Christ being without sin ([bible to="Hebrews 4:15" /], [bible to="2 Corinthians 5:21" /]). One of the characteristics of matzoh bread is that it usually has darker stripes from being cooked, which is symbolic of the scourging Christ endured so “by His stripes we are healed” ([bible to="Mark 15:15" /], [bible to="Isaiah 53:5" /]). When using it for communion, people break off a piece, which is symbolic of Christ’s body being beaten and “crushed for our iniquities” ([bible to="Matthew 26:67" /], [bible to="Mark 15:19" /], [bible to="Isaiah 53:5" /]). This bread reminds us of what Christ endured as He took the punishment for our sins ([bible to="Romans 3:23–26" /]).',
